1. Motivation¶

As a University of Maryland (UMD) Computer Science (CS) student, have you ever struggled with deciding the courses to enroll in? Have you ever encountered a poorly managed course/professor?

UMD students are required to have a minimum of 120 credits, in addition to other requirements, to graduate with their bachelor's degree. There are so many departments students can take classes from and it can be difficult at times to choose which course to take from which department. From libraries to classrooms, there is one commonality we are all concerned about. You may have already guessed it, it is indeed the struggle of what courses to take every semester. Selecting what classes to enroll in was a constant struggle every semester. Even though we all had 4-year plans prepped, it was persistently changing for a multitude of reasons. A couple of those reasons being classes filling up before we could sign up or our interests would change.

When things don't go as planned, it can be very stressful, especially when students have to plan in the middle of their semesters. We would like to help alleviate that stress for CS students. In this tutorial, we will analyze UMD departments, shed light on the CMSC department, and provide CMSC general requirement recommendations, at the minimum, to help smoothen out the experience for fellow peers.

3. Data Collection/Curation + Parsing¶

3.1. Data Collection¶

First, we needed to get a list of all departments. This information can be found on Testudo's Schedule of Classes. We learned that there are 184 different departments. We used that information to request a list of courses from PlanetTerp's API and took the list of courses to get a list of all sections. It takes more than 15 minutes to make all the requests, so we ran the code once and saved the DataFrame to a CSV file to save time. The following is the code we used to accomplish this:

{python}
# Create empty DataFrame to hold sections.
df = pd.DataFrame()

# Create department list.
department_list = ['AASP', 'AAST', 'AGNR', 'AGST', 'AMSC', 'AMST', 'ANSC', 'ANTH', 'AOSC', 'ARAB', 'ARCH', 'AREC', 'ARHU', 'ARMY', 'ARSC', 'ARTH', 'ARTT', 'ASTR', 'BCHM', 'BIOE', 'BIOL', 'BIOM', 'BIPH', 'BISI', 'BMGT', 'BMSO', 'BSCI', 'BSCV', 'BSGC', 'BSOS', 'BSST', 'BUAC', 'BUDT', 'BUFN', 'BULM', 'BUMK', 'BUSI', 'BUSM', 'BUSO', 'CBMG', 'CCJS', 'CHBE', 'CHEM', 'CHIN', 'CHPH', 'CHSE', 'CLAS', 'CLFS', 'CMLT', 'CMSC', 'COMM', 'CPBE', 'CPET', 'CPGH', 'CPJT', 'CPMS', 'CPPL', 'CPSA', 'CPSD', 'CPSF', 'CPSG', 'CPSN', 'CPSP', 'CPSS', 'DANC', 'DATA', 'ECON', 'EDCP', 'EDHD', 'EDHI', 'EDMS', 'EDSP', 'EDUC', 'ENAE', 'ENBC', 'ENCE', 'ENCH', 'ENCO', 'ENEB', 'ENEE', 'ENES', 'ENFP', 'ENGL', 'ENMA', 'ENME', 'ENPM', 'ENRE', 'ENSE', 'ENSP', 'ENST', 'ENTM', 'ENTS', 'EPIB', 'FGSM', 'FILM', 'FIRE', 'FMSC', 'FREN', 'GEMS', 'GEOG', 'GEOL', 'GERM', 'GREK', 'GVPT', 'HACS', 'HDCC', 'HEBR', 'HESI', 'HESP', 'HHUM', 'HISP', 'HIST', 'HLSA', 'HLSC', 'HLTH', 'HNUH', 'HONR', 'IDEA', 'IMDM', 'IMMR', 'INAG', 'INFM', 'INST', 'ISRL', 'ITAL', 'JAPN', 'JOUR', 'JWST', 'KNES', 'KORA', 'LARC', 'LASC', 'LATN', 'LBSC', 'LGBT', 'LING', 'MATH', 'MEES', 'MIEH', 'MITH', 'MLAW', 'MLSC', 'MOCB', 'MSML', 'MUED', 'MUSC', 'MUSP', 'NACS', 'NAVY', 'NEUR', 'NFSC', 'NIAS', 'PEER', 'PERS', 'PHIL', 'PHPE', 'PHSC', 'PHYS', 'PLCY', 'PLSC', 'PORT', 'PSYC', 'RDEV', 'RELS', 'RUSS', 'SLAA', 'SLLC', 'SMLP', 'SOCY', 'SPAN', 'SPHL', 'STAT', 'SURV', 'TDPS', 'THET', 'TLPL', 'TLTC', 'UMEI', 'UNIV', 'URSP', 'USLT', 'VMSC', 'WGSS', 'WMST']

# Get sections from all departments.
for department in department_list:
    # Create empty section list.
    section_list = []

    # Get all courses from department.
    courses = planetterp.courses(department=department)

    try:
        # Get all sections from courses.
        for course in courses:
                for section in planetterp.grades(course=f'{department}{course["course_number"]}'):
                    section_list.append(section)
    except:
        print('error')

    # Add sections to DataFrame.
    df = df.append(pd.DataFrame(section_list), ignore_index=True)

# Save DataFrame to a CSV file.
df.to_csv('data.csv')

We can see by counting the number of NaN or null values, there are missing values for professor. This might mean that the section was entered into the database incorrectly. We decided to keep these sections because it is still valuable for course analysis.

Additionally, there are no other missing values in the other columns. We do not need to do additional cleaning for missing data, but we do need to remove courses that have appeared for only 1 semester because it could be the professor's first time teaching that class. The data would not be as reliable since professors may not be as experienced when they only taught the course once. We agreed that these 1 semester courses is not enough to say that they will grade and teach the class the same way next time. Thus, the following code will remove the courses taht appeared for only 1 semester.

In [518]:

df_new = df_new[df_new['semester'] >= 2]

# Save the courses to keep in a list.
keep_lst = df_new['course'].tolist()

# Remove the course rows that is not in keep_lst list.
df = df[df['course'].isin(keep_lst)]

4. Data Management/Representation/Exploratory Data Analysis¶

4.1 Data Management¶

First, we need to add more columns to the DataFrame. Adding the total number of grades, the total number of passing grades, and the passing percentage would be useful information. We consider passing as having a C- or above.

In [519]:
# Get the total number grades. 
df['number_of_grades'] = df[['A+', 'A', 'A-', 'B+', 'B', 'B-', 'C+', 'C', 'C-', 'D+', 'D', 'D-', 'F', 'W', 'Other']].sum(axis=1)

# Get the total number of passing grades.
df['passing_grades'] = df[['A+', 'A', 'A-', 'B+', 'B', 'B-', 'C+', 'C', 'C-', 'Other']].sum(axis=1)

# Get the pass percentages.
df['passing_percentage'] = ((df['passing_grades'] / df['number_of_grades']) * 100).round(2)

# Covert column as strings.
df['semester'] = df['semester'].astype(str)

# Create year and department columns.
df['year'] = df['semester'].str[0:4]
df['department'] = df['course'].str[0:4]

# Display dataframe.

4.2.1 What are top 10 biggest departments over time?¶

Now we want to know the total number of students in each department to see how the top 10 biggest departments change over time.

In [522]:
# Goal is to make barcharts of total students per year (2012-2020) for each department.
# Group dataframe by department and year.
spy_df = df.groupby(['year','department']).sum().reset_index()

# Create a dataframe with the top most popular departments for each year.
top10 = pd.DataFrame()
for i,e in spy_df.groupby('year'):
  e = e.nlargest(10, columns='number_of_grades')
  top10 = pd.concat([top10, e])

plt.figure(figsize=(17,15))

# Make barplots according to year and department.
for i,e in top10.groupby('year'):
  if i == '2012':
    plt.subplot(3,3,1)
    plt.bar(e['department'], e['number_of_grades'])
    plt.title(i)
  elif i == '2013':
    plt.subplot(3,3,2)
    plt.bar(e['department'], e['number_of_grades'])
    plt.title(i)
  elif i == '2014':
    plt.subplot(3,3,3)
    plt.bar(e['department'], e['number_of_grades'])
    plt.title(i)
  elif i == '2015':
    plt.subplot(3,3,4)
    plt.bar(e['department'], e['number_of_grades'])
    plt.title(i)
  elif i == '2016':
    plt.subplot(3,3,5)

    plt.title(i)

    plt.subplot(3,3,6)

We can see that BMGT and Math departments are the two largest student bodies at UMD. Surprisingly, the CMSC department is not in the top 10 biggest departments until 2014. The CMSC department continued to grow rapidly over the years and is now (in 2020) the third biggest department, passing CHEM at No. 3 since 2012.

In [538]:
# Covert year column to float.
cs_df['year'] = cs_df['year'].astype(float)

# Set the plot size.
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 12))

# Calculate linear regression.
regline = LinearRegression().fit(cs_df[['year']], cs_df['passing_percentage'])
m = regline.coef_
b = regline.intercept_

# Create a scatterplot to view the regression line.
lin_reg_sct = sns.scatterplot(data=cs_df, 
                              x='year', 
                              y='passing_percentage')

# Set the labels and title.
lin_reg_sct.set_xlabel('Year', 
                       fontsize=15)
lin_reg_sct.set_ylabel('Passing Percentage', 
                       fontsize=15)
lin_reg_sct.set_title('Predicted Passing Percentage Over Time', 
                      fontsize=18)

# Add the regression line.
plt.plot(cs_df[['year']], 
         regline.predict(cs_df[['year']]), 
         label=f'y = {b.item():.4f} + {m.item():.4f}x', 
         color='r')

# Set legend.
plt.legend(title='Linear Regression Model',
           bbox_to_anchor=(1.01, 1),
           borderaxespad=0)

# Show plot.
plt.show()

From the graph above, there is a positive linear increasing trend. Our linear regression equation is:

  • y = -1197.7737 + 0.6353x

If we plug in 2021 for x, we get 86.220215. We can conclude that the average pass rate for the CMSC department in 2021 will be 86.22%.

6. Communication of Insights Attained¶

We ended up with many conclusions that may have been lost in the prose above. We want to gather them all in one place and summarize our findings.

  1. The CMSC department wasn't in the top 10 at UMD until 2014. In 2020, it is now the 3rd largest department.
  2. The pass rate of the CMSC department is much lower compared to other departments by almost 7%.
  3. The top 10 courses and professors may be too old to be useful.
  4. The top 10 Upper-Level Concentration include smaller departments.
  5. The average pass rate for CMSC courses has gotten better over time from 81% to 87%.
  6. The predicted pass rate for 2021 is 86.22%.
  7. COVID-19 had a significant impact on students shown in our analysis. The average pass rate is almost 5% higher than other semesters.

The professors we recommend for required computer science major courses are:

  • CMSC131 Roger Eastman (82.60%) or
  • CMSC133 Swati Singhal (100%)
  • CMSC132 Pedram Sadeghian (89.41%)
  • CMSC216 Pedram Sadeghian (93.01%)
  • CMSC250 Roger Eastman (91.11%)
  • CMSC330 Thomas Gilray (94.12%)
  • CMSC351 Mohammad Nayeem Teli (84.35%)

We expect 2021 to follow the same trend. Students were allowed to choose pass/fail this Spring 2021 semester, but the cutoff is C- or above. The predicted pass rate of 86.22% with our linear regression model may be slightly higher than the actual pass rate once grades are released for this semester.
